{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":1,"timestamp":1778726646,"nonce":"XeKjxI8sBN+3gsHSACRxWrUHCEs=","title":"Synthesis: bridging cs2019 induction to RNN training methods (Codex consultation 2026-05-13)","message":"## Framing (note: this is a synthesis, not a settled conclusion)\n\nThis issue records a Codex consultation conducted 2026-05-13 in response to a substantive concern raised during the b399efc post-matrix discussion: **is our current adversarial training setup (LinearDynamicsAdversary with one ΔA per replicate, PGD inner loop) actually inducing the kind of robustness we want — i.e., the kind cs2019 demonstrate in humans and the analytical Riccati solver — or is the controller silently co-adapting to a fixed adversary?**\n\nThe consultation surfaced significant reframing beyond the original concern. Treat the content below as the current best-available reasoning; future agents reading this should not take any conclusion as load-bearing without re-verifying against the linked materials. Two prior archaeology passes informed the consultation prompt and corrected earlier Claude framings (especially regarding `410d7ac` — the regulator-vs-tracker MVP was structurally degenerate, not a null result).\n\n## What is in this issue\n\nThis issue body holds the synthesised conclusions and recommendations. The full record — prompt, raw Codex response, Claude-side summary — lives in the companion consultations directory at `results/\u003cthis-issue-prefix\u003e/consultations/2026-05-13_adversarial_training_synthesis/`.\n\n## Codex's central reframe\n\nThe load-bearing axis is NOT \"saddle point vs co-adaptation.\" It is:\n\n1. What uncertainty channel is being robustified?\n2. What cost schedule makes speed useful rather than wasteful?\n3. Is the policy forced to couple nominal movement speed to feedback gain, or can it decouple them?\n4. Has the inner maximization actually found the worst case?\n\nThe user's original \"is fixed adversary actually adversarial\" worry is real but mis-attributed: the failure mode is not \"fixed adversary\" in the abstract (LQ/H∞ controllers also converge to fixed policies against fixed worst-case solutions), but the combination \"nonconvex RNN + one learned adversary per replicate + weakly-verified PGD inner loop + no held-out worst-case audit.\" The right test is to freeze the controller and re-run strong independent adversary search with many restarts and step counts. `89891ab` is the load-bearing gate for trusting any minimax claim.\n\nCritically: **the current `LinearDynamicsAdversary` (flavor-(b)) is a different game from cs2019's Eqs 11-13**, which read as full-state additive ε H∞. The empirical −25% mean Δv from flavor-B training (`c723082` comment `c87b273`) is not surprising in this light — a state-multiplicative adversary makes \"keep state small / move slower\" optimal, which is the opposite of what cs2019 observes.\n\n## Multi-signature prediction table (from Codex)\n\n| Training regime | Speed Δv | Feedback-gain modulation |\n|---|---:|---:|\n| Standard expected-cost + perturbation training | no / tiny | yes, modest (LQG-like) |\n| CVaR / APT / PAI-ASF | no / tiny | yes, stronger (matches `844ef95` observation) |\n| Gaussian bump minimax | unlikely | likely |\n| Current ΔA flavor-B | mixed / negative mean | unclear / channel-specific |\n| LEQG alone | maybe small | yes |\n| Full-state ε H∞-matched | **most likely** | **most likely** |\n| H∞ Riccati teacher distillation | (existence check) | yes if architecture can express it |\n\nVerdict: **feedback-gain modulation is broad and easy; speed inflation is narrow** — appears when robust-gain inflation is tied to nominal steering by the plant/cost/controller parameterisation. RNNs may learn tracker-like decompositions that preserve FB robustness while leaving nominal speed flat.\n\n## Codex's recommended next experiment (must-do)\n\nImplement the full-state ε adversary matching cs2019 Eq 13, with cs2019's `(t/N)^6` cost schedule and matched horizon/delay. This single experiment folds `020a65b`, `89891ab`, `6ec6b19`, `daa48c8` into one decisive test.\n\n- Adversary: free time-varying full-state ε_t, L2-bounded over rollout\n- Training: minimax, with PGD step sweep `{5, 20, 50}` and independent restarts\n- Arms: **linear regulator first as a Riccati round-trip gate; one GRU arm only after the linear arm matches Riccati**\n- Evaluation: replicate-conditioned (no group means alone), multi-signature (Δv, feedback-gain/step-response, induced gain by channel, endpoint/lateral deviation, held-out adversary loss)\n- Success: linear regulator recovers Riccati's +Δv signature; GRU either also recovers OR cleanly dissociates gain from speed\n- Failure: linear fails → training/eval pipeline is not the H∞ game; stop GRU interpretation until fixed\n\nCheap unblocker before compute: `b6084c7` Tier-0 audit (~2h on existing artifacts).\n\n## What to deprioritise (per Codex)\n\n- More flavor-B η sweeps\n- Population adversaries (`--n-adversaries K \u003e 1`) as the central effort\n- Regulator-vs-tracker architecture comparisons — until the matched ε round-trip works\n- Muscle/biomechanics work\n- LEQG-alone\n- Broad reach-geometry sweeps\n- Interpretability-first GRU decomposition (becomes valuable AFTER a trained GRU with verified robustness signature exists)\n\n## Cross-references\n\n**The synthesis directly conflicts with or supersedes claims in:**\n- `c99ad9d` comment `c5979ea` — partial: the (a)/(b) retraction is consistent with this synthesis, but the broader implication (\"we need a different adversary class entirely\") is new\n- `f695729` body — partial: the phase umbrella's regulator-vs-tracker framing is one option among many in Codex's axis, not the central one\n\n**Materials the synthesis builds on:**\n- `results/72fb8d9/synthesis.md` (synthesis doc of record, especially §8.0)\n- `results/b557d4e/synthesis_review.md` (original formal (a)/(b) argument)\n- `results/d448c9d/consultations/2026-05-11_decoupling_framing/` (prior consultation that established the multi-hypothesis menu)\n- `results/844ef95/README.md` lines 67-69 (canonical feedback-gain-vs-velocity dissociation)\n- `results/410d7ac/notes/decoupling_acid_test_mvp.md` (the structurally-degenerate MVP)\n\n**Adversary class issues:**\n- `c723082` (LinearDynamicsAdversary impl; comment `c87b273` has the negative-Δv result)\n- `020a65b` (full-state ε adversary, the recommended next implementation)\n- `eb7fb9f` (LEQG ≠ backdoor to (b))\n- `97c227a` (Riccati flavor-(b) S-procedure, closed insufficient)\n\n**Gating prerequisites:**\n- `89891ab` (PGD-step verification — load-bearing for trusting any minimax claim)\n- `6ec6b19` (cost-schedule (t/N)^α sweep — cs2019 uses α=6)\n- `daa48c8` (bimodal-replicate analysis — for reporting)\n- `b6084c7` (Tier-0 audit — cheap pre-compute unblocker)\n\n**Capacity/teacher checks:**\n- `db35426` (H∞ Riccati teacher distillation)\n\n**Decision records that constrain the work:**\n- `a04711e` (k=10 damping choice)\n- `08c49e3` (τ=50ms force-filter choice)\n\n**Coordination:**\n- `c99ad9d` (training-methods) — primary scope\n- `4d38c15` (analyses) — for multi-signature evaluation protocol\n- `b33e8da` (phases) — affects how active phase `f695729` is interpreted\n- `f695729` (regulator-coupling phase umbrella)\n\n**The implementation plan for the must-do experiment is NOT in this issue.** A separate child issue will be filed for that, with this issue as parent.","files":null}]}